# Introduction

This document describes the planned evolution of the Humanitarian Connection Protocol (HCP).

Unlike the HCP Specifications, this roadmap is informative.

It does not define normative protocol behavior.

Instead, it communicates the long-term direction of the project and the major milestones planned for future development.

The roadmap may evolve as the protocol matures.

---

# Vision

HCP aims to become an open, implementation-independent interoperability standard for humanitarian observations.

The protocol is designed to enable organizations, institutions, communities and software systems to exchange structured humanitarian information while preserving:

* decentralization;
* interoperability;
* explainability;
* privacy;
* implementation independence.

The roadmap reflects this long-term vision.

---

# Development Philosophy

HCP evolves in incremental phases.

Each phase builds upon the previous one while preserving protocol stability whenever reasonably possible.

The project prioritizes:

* architectural consistency;
* semantic interoperability;
* backward compatibility;
* implementation simplicity;
* long-term maintainability.

Features are introduced only when they improve humanitarian interoperability.

